{"title_page": "Opal Tometi", "text_new": "{{short description|Nigerian\u2013American writer, strategist and community organizer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Opal Tometi\n| image              = Opal Tometi.jpg\n| birth_date         = {{birth based on age as of date |32 |2016|August|29}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Williams |first1=Lauren N. |title=An Influencer from the African Diaspora Who Started an American Movement |url=http://time.com/4463742/opal-tometi-american-voices/ |work=Time |date=August 29, 2016}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Arizona]]\n| occupation         = Activist, writer\n| known_for          = [[Black Lives Matter]], Black Alliance for Just Immigration\n| website            = http://www.opaltometi.org\n}}\n\n'''Opal Tometi''' is a [[Nigerian-American, writer, strategist, and community organizer. She is a co-founder of [[Black Lives Matter]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dalton|first1=Deron|title=The Three Women Behind the Black Lives Matter Movement|url=http://madamenoire.com/528287/the-three-women-behind-the-black-lives-matter-movement/|website=Madame Noire|date=May 4, 2015|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref> She is currently the Executive Director at BAJI (Black Alliance for Just Immigration).\n\nTometi is the co-founder of Black Lives Matter. She brought attention to the racial inequities faced by Black people. Before that, Tometi was an active community organizer in her hometown advocating for human rights issues. She has campaigned for advancing human rights, migrant rights, and racial justice worldwide.\n\nShe has appeared in several media outlets, including Glamour,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.glamour.com/story/women-of-the-year-black-lives-matter-founders|title=Meet the Women Founders of Black Lives Matter|last=Meyerson|first=Collier|work=Glamour|access-date=2018-11-26|language=en}}</ref> Essence,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.essence.com/culture/black-lives-matter-founders-women-of-year-glamour/|title=Black Lives Matter Founders Chosen As Glamour's \"Women Of The Year\" Essence|work=Essence|access-date=2018-11-26|language=en-US}}</ref> CNN,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/interactive/2015/08/us/disruptors/|title=The Disruptors|access-date=2018-11-26|language=en-US}}</ref> MSNBC,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/watch/when-blacklivesmatter-we-wont-have-to-say-black-lives-matter-401643075768?v=railb&|title=When #BlackLivesMatter we won't have to say 'black lives matter'|work=MSNBC.com|access-date=2018-11-26|language=en-US}}</ref> and BET.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bet.com/shows/black-girls-rock/2016/awards/community-change-agent.html|title=Community Change Agent|last=|first=|date=|website=BET.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> Her written works have been published by several media outlets including ''[[The Huffington Post]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Opal Tometi|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/opal-tometi/|website=The Huffington Post|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref> and [[Time (magazine)|''Time.'']]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/author/opal-tometi/|title=Opal Tometi|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2018-11-26}}</ref> Tometi continues to collaborate with communities in [[Los Angeles]], [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[New York City]], [[Oakland, California|Oakland]], [[Washington, D.C.|Washington D.C.]] and communities throughout the [[Southern United States|Southern states]].\n\n==Personal life and education==\nOpal Tometi is the daughter of [[Nigerian American|Nigerian immigrants]]. She is the oldest of three children and has two younger brothers. She grew up in [[Phoenix, Arizona]], and now lives in [[Brooklyn, New York]]. She received a Bachelor of Arts degree in History and a Masters in Communications and Advocacy from the [[University of Arizona]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Armstrong|first1=Lisa|title=Civil Rights Leaders|url=http://www.blackalliance.org/essence-magazine-the-new-civil-rights-leaders/|website=Black Alliance|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref> On May 7, 2016, she received an honorary doctor of science degree from [[Clarkson University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.clarkson.edu/news/2016/news-release_2016-05-07-06.html|title=Opal Tometi Awarded Clarkson University Honorary Degree|date=May 7, 2016|website=www.clarkson.edu|publisher=Clarkson University|access-date=June 19, 2016}}</ref>  Tometi is a former Case Manager for survivors of domestic violence and still provides community education on the issue.\n\n==Activism==\n\n===Black Lives Matter===\nTometi joined with [[Patrisse Cullors]] and [[Alicia Garza]] to give shape to the Black Lives Matter group. Tometi is credited with setting up the [[social media]] aspects of the movement.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Day|first1=Elizabeth|title=#BlackLivesMatter: the Birth of a New Civil Rights Movement|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jul/19/blacklivesmatter-birth-civil-rights-movement|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=July 19, 2015|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Black Alliance for Just Immigration ===\nPrior to becoming Executive Director of BAJI, Tometi worked as Co-Director and Communications Director. Her contributions include leading organizing efforts for the first ever Black-led rally for immigrant justice and the first Congressional briefing on Black immigrants in Washington DC.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n==Other==\nTometi has spoken at [[Susquehanna University]], the Facing Race Conference of 2012, the [[Aspen Institute]]'s Ideas Summit, and the Grinnell College Technology and Human Rights Symposium.<ref name=Susquehanna>{{cite web|title=#BlackLivesMatter Founder to Speak at Susquehanna University|url=https://www.susqu.edu/about-su/newsroom/blacklivesmatter-founder-to-speak-at-susquehanna|website=Susquehanna University|date=September 4, 2015|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Dinan|first1=Stephen|title=Black Lives Matter is Message of 'Love' for All: Founder|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2015/sep/30/opal-tometi-black-lives-matter-message-love-all/|website=The Washington Times|date=September 30, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Opal Tometi|url=https://facingrace.raceforward.org/speaker/opal-tometi|website=Facing Race}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grinnell.edu/news/technology-and-human-rights-symposium|title=Technology and Human Rights Symposium {{!}} Grinnell College|website=www.grinnell.edu|language=en|date=March 7\u201310, 2017|access-date=March 11, 2017}}</ref> She has presented at the United Nations and has participated with the United Nations Global Forum on Migration and the [[Commission on the Status of Women]].<ref name=Susquehanna /> While at The University of Arizona,   Tometi volunteered with the [[American Civil Liberties Union]]. She is additionally involved with Black Organizing for Leadership and Dignity<ref>[http://boldorganizing.org/ Black Organizing for Leadership and Dignity] (BOLD) website.</ref> and is a member of [[Theta Nu Xi Multicultural Sorority, Inc.]]\n\n==Recognition and awards==\nTometi was featured as a new [[civil rights leader]] by ''[[Essence Magazine]]'' in 2014 and by the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dandes|first1=Rick|title=How Friends Tapped Power of Social Media to Start a Movement|url=http://www.dailyitem.com/news/how-friends-tapped-power-of-social-media-to-start-a/article_377ddf64-60d3-11e5-93f3-b3d056ce6798.html|website=The Daily Item|date=September 21, 2015|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref> She was listed in the Root 100 list of African American Achievers between 25 and 45.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Root 100|url=http://www.theroot.com/articles/lists/2015/09/the_root_100_2015.html|website=The Root|accessdate=October 15, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151012102135/http://www.theroot.com/articles/lists/2015/09/the_root_100_2015.html|archive-date=October 12, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> She was listed in the ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'' Top 100 list of extraordinary women. Along with Garza and Cullors, Tometi was named to the 2013 [[Time (magazine)]] 100 Women of the Year<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5793789/black-lives-matter-founders-100-women-of-the-year/|title=Black Lives Matter Founders: 100 Women of the Year|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-04-27}}</ref> and Politico 50 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/politico50/2015/|title=The POLITICO 50|website=POLITICO Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-01-20}}</ref> Guide to Thinkers, Doers, and Visionaries.<ref>{{cite web|title=Politico 50|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/politico50/2015/alicia-garza-patrisse-cullors-opal-tometi|website=Politico|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref> In 2016, she was, alongside her co-founders, on [[Fortune (magazine)|''Fortune'']]'s list of \"World's Greatest Leaders\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2016/03/24/black-lives-matter-great-leaders/|title=The Black Lives Matter Founders Are Among the World's Greatest Leaders|work=Fortune|access-date=2018-11-26|language=en}}</ref> She was awarded the [[Letelier-Moffitt Human Rights Award]] in 2017.<ref name=\"lmhra\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ips-dc.org/letelier-moffitt-human-rights-awards/ |title= The Letelier-Moffitt Human Rights Awards |publisher=[[Institute for Policy Studies]] |accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref> She is also featured in the Smithsonian's [[National Museum of African American History and Culture|National Museum for African American History and Culture]] (NMAAHC).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/27/arts/design/how-do-you-tell-the-story-of-black-america-in-one-museum.html?_r=0|title=How Do You Tell the Story of Black America in One Museum?|access-date=2018-11-26|language=en}}</ref>  In 2018, Tometi was featured in the Guardian's list of 200 leaders <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/ng-interactive/2018/jul/05/the-frederick-douglass-200|title=The Frederick Douglass 200: the people who embody the abolitionist's spirit and work|last=Adolphe|first=Juweek|last2=Morris|first2=Sam|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2019-01-20}}</ref> who embody the work of Frederick Douglass. In 2019, along with co-authors [[Alicia Garza]] and Patrisse Khan-Cullors, Tometi received a [[PEN Oakland awards|PEN Oakland Josephine Miles Literary Award]] for ''When They Call You a Terrorist: A Black Lives Matter Memoir''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|Opal Tometi}}\n\n{{Black Lives Matter}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tometi, Opal}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:American political activists]]\n[[Category:Black Lives Matter people]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona alumni]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:American people of Nigerian descent]]\n[[Category:Activists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Nigerian\u2013American writer, strategist and community organizer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Opal Tometi\n| image              = Opal Tometi.jpg\n| birth_date         = {{birth based on age as of date |32 |2016|August|29}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Williams |first1=Lauren N. |title=An Influencer from the African Diaspora Who Started an American Movement |url=http://time.com/4463742/opal-tometi-american-voices/ |work=Time |date=August 29, 2016}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Arizona]]\n| occupation         = Activist, writer\n| known_for          = [[Black Lives Matter]], Black Alliance for Just Immigration\n| website            = http://www.opaltometi.org\n}}\n\n'''Opal Tometi''' is a [[Nigerian-American]] human rights activist, writer, strategist, and community organizer. She is a co-founder of [[Black Lives Matter]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dalton|first1=Deron|title=The Three Women Behind the Black Lives Matter Movement|url=http://madamenoire.com/528287/the-three-women-behind-the-black-lives-matter-movement/|website=Madame Noire|date=May 4, 2015|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref> She is currently the Executive Director at BAJI (Black Alliance for Just Immigration).\n\nTometi is the co-founder of Black Lives Matter. She brought attention to the racial inequities faced by Black people. Before that, Tometi was an active community organizer in her hometown advocating for human rights issues. She has campaigned for advancing human rights, migrant rights, and racial justice worldwide.\n\nShe has appeared in several media outlets, including Glamour,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.glamour.com/story/women-of-the-year-black-lives-matter-founders|title=Meet the Women Founders of Black Lives Matter|last=Meyerson|first=Collier|work=Glamour|access-date=2018-11-26|language=en}}</ref> Essence,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.essence.com/culture/black-lives-matter-founders-women-of-year-glamour/|title=Black Lives Matter Founders Chosen As Glamour's \"Women Of The Year\" Essence|work=Essence|access-date=2018-11-26|language=en-US}}</ref> CNN,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/interactive/2015/08/us/disruptors/|title=The Disruptors|access-date=2018-11-26|language=en-US}}</ref> MSNBC,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/watch/when-blacklivesmatter-we-wont-have-to-say-black-lives-matter-401643075768?v=railb&|title=When #BlackLivesMatter we won't have to say 'black lives matter'|work=MSNBC.com|access-date=2018-11-26|language=en-US}}</ref> and BET.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bet.com/shows/black-girls-rock/2016/awards/community-change-agent.html|title=Community Change Agent|last=|first=|date=|website=BET.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> Her written works have been published by several media outlets including ''[[The Huffington Post]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Opal Tometi|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/opal-tometi/|website=The Huffington Post|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref> and [[Time (magazine)|''Time.'']]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/author/opal-tometi/|title=Opal Tometi|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2018-11-26}}</ref> Tometi continues to collaborate with communities in [[Los Angeles]], [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[New York City]], [[Oakland, California|Oakland]], [[Washington, D.C.|Washington D.C.]] and communities throughout the [[Southern United States|Southern states]].\n\n==Personal life and education==\nOpal Tometi is the daughter of [[Nigerian American|Nigerian immigrants]]. She is the oldest of three children and has two younger brothers. She grew up in [[Phoenix, Arizona]], and now lives in [[Brooklyn, New York]]. She received a Bachelor of Arts degree in History and a Masters in Communications and Advocacy from the [[University of Arizona]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Armstrong|first1=Lisa|title=Civil Rights Leaders|url=http://www.blackalliance.org/essence-magazine-the-new-civil-rights-leaders/|website=Black Alliance|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref> On May 7, 2016, she received an honorary doctor of science degree from [[Clarkson University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.clarkson.edu/news/2016/news-release_2016-05-07-06.html|title=Opal Tometi Awarded Clarkson University Honorary Degree|date=May 7, 2016|website=www.clarkson.edu|publisher=Clarkson University|access-date=June 19, 2016}}</ref>  Tometi is a former Case Manager for survivors of domestic violence and still provides community education on the issue.\n\n==Activism==\n\n===Black Lives Matter===\nTometi joined with [[Patrisse Cullors]] and [[Alicia Garza]] to give shape to the Black Lives Matter group. Tometi is credited with setting up the [[social media]] aspects of the movement.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Day|first1=Elizabeth|title=#BlackLivesMatter: the Birth of a New Civil Rights Movement|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jul/19/blacklivesmatter-birth-civil-rights-movement|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=July 19, 2015|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Black Alliance for Just Immigration ===\nPrior to becoming Executive Director of BAJI, Tometi worked as Co-Director and Communications Director. Her contributions include leading organizing efforts for the first ever Black-led rally for immigrant justice and the first Congressional briefing on Black immigrants in Washington DC.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n==Other==\nTometi has spoken at [[Susquehanna University]], the Facing Race Conference of 2012, the [[Aspen Institute]]'s Ideas Summit, and the Grinnell College Technology and Human Rights Symposium.<ref name=Susquehanna>{{cite web|title=#BlackLivesMatter Founder to Speak at Susquehanna University|url=https://www.susqu.edu/about-su/newsroom/blacklivesmatter-founder-to-speak-at-susquehanna|website=Susquehanna University|date=September 4, 2015|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Dinan|first1=Stephen|title=Black Lives Matter is Message of 'Love' for All: Founder|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2015/sep/30/opal-tometi-black-lives-matter-message-love-all/|website=The Washington Times|date=September 30, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Opal Tometi|url=https://facingrace.raceforward.org/speaker/opal-tometi|website=Facing Race}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grinnell.edu/news/technology-and-human-rights-symposium|title=Technology and Human Rights Symposium {{!}} Grinnell College|website=www.grinnell.edu|language=en|date=March 7\u201310, 2017|access-date=March 11, 2017}}</ref> She has presented at the United Nations and has participated with the United Nations Global Forum on Migration and the [[Commission on the Status of Women]].<ref name=Susquehanna /> While at The University of Arizona,   Tometi volunteered with the [[American Civil Liberties Union]]. She is additionally involved with Black Organizing for Leadership and Dignity<ref>[http://boldorganizing.org/ Black Organizing for Leadership and Dignity] (BOLD) website.</ref> and is a member of [[Theta Nu Xi Multicultural Sorority, Inc.]]\n\n==Recognition and awards==\nTometi was featured as a new [[civil rights leader]] by ''[[Essence Magazine]]'' in 2014 and by the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dandes|first1=Rick|title=How Friends Tapped Power of Social Media to Start a Movement|url=http://www.dailyitem.com/news/how-friends-tapped-power-of-social-media-to-start-a/article_377ddf64-60d3-11e5-93f3-b3d056ce6798.html|website=The Daily Item|date=September 21, 2015|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref> She was listed in the Root 100 list of African American Achievers between 25 and 45.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Root 100|url=http://www.theroot.com/articles/lists/2015/09/the_root_100_2015.html|website=The Root|accessdate=October 15, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151012102135/http://www.theroot.com/articles/lists/2015/09/the_root_100_2015.html|archive-date=October 12, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> She was listed in the ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'' Top 100 list of extraordinary women. Along with Garza and Cullors, Tometi was named to the 2013 [[Time (magazine)]] 100 Women of the Year<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5793789/black-lives-matter-founders-100-women-of-the-year/|title=Black Lives Matter Founders: 100 Women of the Year|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-04-27}}</ref> and Politico 50 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/politico50/2015/|title=The POLITICO 50|website=POLITICO Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-01-20}}</ref> Guide to Thinkers, Doers, and Visionaries.<ref>{{cite web|title=Politico 50|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/politico50/2015/alicia-garza-patrisse-cullors-opal-tometi|website=Politico|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref> In 2016, she was, alongside her co-founders, on [[Fortune (magazine)|''Fortune'']]'s list of \"World's Greatest Leaders\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2016/03/24/black-lives-matter-great-leaders/|title=The Black Lives Matter Founders Are Among the World's Greatest Leaders|work=Fortune|access-date=2018-11-26|language=en}}</ref> She was awarded the [[Letelier-Moffitt Human Rights Award]] in 2017.<ref name=\"lmhra\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ips-dc.org/letelier-moffitt-human-rights-awards/ |title= The Letelier-Moffitt Human Rights Awards |publisher=[[Institute for Policy Studies]] |accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref> She is also featured in the Smithsonian's [[National Museum of African American History and Culture|National Museum for African American History and Culture]] (NMAAHC).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/27/arts/design/how-do-you-tell-the-story-of-black-america-in-one-museum.html?_r=0|title=How Do You Tell the Story of Black America in One Museum?|access-date=2018-11-26|language=en}}</ref>  In 2018, Tometi was featured in the Guardian's list of 200 leaders <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/ng-interactive/2018/jul/05/the-frederick-douglass-200|title=The Frederick Douglass 200: the people who embody the abolitionist's spirit and work|last=Adolphe|first=Juweek|last2=Morris|first2=Sam|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2019-01-20}}</ref> who embody the work of Frederick Douglass. In 2019, along with co-authors [[Alicia Garza]] and Patrisse Khan-Cullors, Tometi received a [[PEN Oakland awards|PEN Oakland Josephine Miles Literary Award]] for ''When They Call You a Terrorist: A Black Lives Matter Memoir''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|Opal Tometi}}\n\n{{Black Lives Matter}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tometi, Opal}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:American political activists]]\n[[Category:Black Lives Matter people]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona alumni]]\n[[Category:American women activists]